        <p>This is the 21th century. We have left the old disciplinary systems largely behind. According to
Deleuze, we have moved from Disciplinary Society (Foucault) towards a Society of Control. This is a
society brought forth by the power of deterritorialization, where despite the appearance of an
unparalled freedom, the diffusion of power places us all the more under the forces of capitalism. An
important aspect of the Society of control is that we are allowed to do “whatever we want.”</p>
    </div>
    <div style="
    padding: 10px;
">
        <p>It presents itself as a kind of freedom. No longer restrained by enclosure structures, like those of the
school or the factory, we can pursue an online education in our time, or work from home. What seems
to be lost here is true “free time”—that would be time fully outside of the structures of power. While it
had its own oppressive power relations, a disciplinary society seems to have had space for this: when
I punch out at the factory, my time is my own, until I go back tomorrow, for another shift. In a society of
control, this increasingly disappears.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="
    padding: 10px;
">
        <p>The effect is the same as with the panopticon: it does not matter if you are actually being watched, but
to create the feeling that you might be under surveillance at any given moment. Yet, in a society of
control, even that feeling is discouraged.</p>
    </div>
<div style="
    padding: 10px;
">
        <p>We know that we are being tracked but are encouraged not to worry about it. In our own time it seems
clear that the power of unions will not save us. We are the &#39;next generation&#39; that Deleuze refers to,
therefore it is up to us to figure how to resist this control. Or not. In the end,</p>
    </div>
    <div style="
    padding: 10px;
">
        <h5>you can do whatever you want.</h5>
    </div>
